    "heroTagline": "Paddle beneath 400-year-old red and white pines",
    "editorialIntro": "If you only get off the Northlander at one stop north of Huntsville, make it Temagami. This is one of the most extraordinary places in Ontario and one of the most undersung wilderness destinations in Canada. The ancient pine forests that surround Temagami are among the last old-growth forests in southern Canada, with trees that were already several centuries old when the first Europeans arrived, trees that have watched the entire history of this country unfold from the lakeshore.\n\nLake Temagami itself is a vast, island-dotted inland sea with over a thousand islands and a canoe route network that has been drawing paddlers for generations. The legendary canoe routes of Temagami, immortalized by Grey Owl and countless wilderness writers, offer some of the finest backcountry paddling on the continent. The lake is also exceptionally clear, cold, and deep, one of those bodies of water that makes you feel something primal about wilderness.\n\nThe village of Temagami is small and genuine. The station sits on the lake and the view from the platform when you arrive is one of the finest railway arrival moments in Canada. Bear Island in the middle of the lake is home to the Teme-Augama Anishinaabe and is accessible by water taxi, a reminder that this landscape has been home to people for thousands of years before the arrival of tourists and trains.",
