    "pageTitle": "Things to Do in Kirkland Lake by Train | Northlander Guide",
    "metaDescription": "Your complete guide to Kirkland Lake by train. Gold rush history, hockey legends, and the Museum of Northern History.",
    "heroTagline": "Gold rush heritage, hockey legends, and proud northern spirit",
    "editorialIntro": "Kirkland Lake is gold country and it wears that history with justified pride. Between 1918 and the 1960s, this town produced more gold than almost any other place on earth. The mines that built it produced a staggering wealth that funded the hockey rinks, the opera house, and the community institutions that still define the town today. The Macassa Mine still operates, making Kirkland Lake one of the few active gold mining communities in Ontario.\n\nThe Museum of Northern History in the Sir Harry Oakes Chateau is one of the finest regional museums in the province. The chateau itself is an extraordinary building, a lakeside mansion built by the gold rush millionaire Harry Oakes who was later murdered in the Bahamas in one of the most famous unsolved crimes of the twentieth century.\n\nThe hockey connection is equally remarkable. Kirkland Lake has produced more NHL players per capita than almost any other community in Canada. Dick Duff, Ralph Backstrom, Ted Lindsay, and many others learned to skate here. The Tim Horton story begins here too, before he died in a car accident on Highway 11 near Cochrane in 1974.",
