    "pageTitle": "Things to Do in Huntsville by Train | Northlander Guide",
    "metaDescription": "Your complete guide to Huntsville on the Northlander route. Arts, adventure, Algonquin Park access, and the best of Muskoka.",
    "heroTagline": "Vibrant arts town and the gateway to Algonquin Park",
    "editorialIntro": "Huntsville is Muskoka's most vibrant town and it wears that vitality with genuine confidence. The arts scene here is remarkable for a community of its size, with galleries, live music venues, and cultural institutions that would not be out of place in a city five times larger. The Algonquin Theatre brings world-class performances to the north and the annual Muskoka Novel Marathon is one of the more wonderfully eccentric literary events in Canada.\n\nThe town sits at the confluence of the Muskoka River and Hunters Bay and the water is everywhere, defining neighbourhoods, creating parks, and giving the town its particular energy. Main Street is lined with independent businesses that have somehow survived and thrived through decades when small-town retail was supposed to be dying. The secret is the locals who live here year-round and who support these businesses with the kind of loyalty that chains can never inspire.\n\nHuntsville is also the gateway to Algonquin Park. The park's east gate is about 45 minutes east and the experience of paddling a canoe into Algonquin from Huntsville is one of the defining Ontario adventures. If you come for one night, you might find reasons to stay for three.",
