    "editorialIntro": "Gravenhurst is where Muskoka begins in earnest and it announces itself beautifully. The town sits at the southern tip of Lake Muskoka, the largest lake in a region famous for its lakes, and the waterfront has been drawing visitors since the Victorian era when wealthy Torontonians first discovered that the Shield country north of the city was one of the most spectacular landscapes in the world.\n\nThe crown jewel of Gravenhurst is the RMS Segwun, the oldest operating steamship in North America, which has been carrying passengers on Lake Muskoka since 1887. Watching it pull away from the Muskoka Wharf with its whistle blowing is one of those genuinely Canadian moments that you find yourself describing to people for years afterward. The Muskoka Wharf area itself has been beautifully developed with shops, restaurants, and galleries all within easy walking distance of the water.\n\nGravenhurst is also the birthplace of Dr Norman Bethune, the Canadian physician who became a hero of the Chinese revolution and is celebrated there more than almost anywhere in Canada. The Bethune Memorial House is a fascinating piece of Canadian history that most Canadians have never visited. Come for the steamship, stay for the story.",
